{"cursor":"33770","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n'Speciation' is the evolutionary process by which new biological species arise.\nThe biologist Orator F. Cook seems to have been the first to coin the term\n'speciation' for the splitting of lineages or \"cladogenesis,\" as opposed to\n\"anagenesis\" or \"phyletic evolution\" occurring within\nlineages. Whether genetic drift is a minor or major\ncontributor to speciation is the subject matter of much ongoing discussion.\n\nThere are four geographic modes of speciation in nature, based on the extent to\nwhich speciating populations are isolated from one another: allopatric,\nperipatric, parapatric, and sympatric. Speciation may also be induced\nartificially, through animal husbandry, agriculture, or laboratory experiments.\nObserved examples of each kind of speciation are provided throughout. [http://www.talkorigins.org/faqs/faq-\nspeciation.html Observed Instances of Speciation] by Joseph Boxhorn. Retrieved 8\nJune 2009.\n","linknr":734,"url":"Speciation","recorded":1362509379,"links":70,"instances":["california","biology","ocean","genetic_algorithm","biology","island","biology"],"pdf":["http://dba.fc.ul.pt/evo/textos/mayr_punctuated.pdf","http://dba.fc.ul.pt/evo/textos/mayr_punctuated.pdf","http://oldweb.northampton.ac.uk/aps/env/lbrg/journals/papers/OllertonHeredityCommentary2005.pdf","http://oldweb.northampton.ac.uk/aps/env/lbrg/journals/papers/OllertonHeredityCommentary2005.pdf"],"categories":["Ecology","Evolutionary biology","Speciation|*"],"headings":["Natural speciation","Artificial speciation","Genetics","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/CollapsedtreeLabels-simplified.svg/200px-CollapsedtreeLabels-simplified.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Tree_of_life.svg/16px-Tree_of_life.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/48/Folder_Hexagonal_Icon.svg/16px-Folder_H